# Python Variables, Constants, and Print Function Demonstration

This Python script demonstrates the use of variables, constants, and various print function techniques.

## Code Example

```python
# Demonstrating Variables, Constants, and Print Function

# CONSTANTS (conventionally written in uppercase)
PI = 3.14159
GRAVITY = 9.8
COMPANY_NAME = "TechCorp Inc."
MAX_USERS = 1000

# Variables (can change during program execution)
radius = 5.0
user_name = "Alice"
user_age = 25
is_active = True
temperature = 72.5

# Print function demonstrations
print("=== CONSTANTS ===")
print(f"Value of PI: {PI}")
print(f"Gravity on Earth: {GRAVITY} m/s²")
print(f"Company: {COMPANY_NAME}")
print(f"Maximum users allowed: {MAX_USERS}")
print()

print("=== VARIABLES ===")
print(f"Radius: {radius}")
print(f"User Name: {user_name}")
print(f"Age: {user_age}")
print(f"Active Status: {is_active}")
print(f"Temperature: {temperature}°F")
print()

# Changing variable values
print("=== UPDATING VARIABLES ===")
radius = 7.5  # Update the radius
user_age = 26  # Happy birthday!
temperature = 68.0  # Temperature changed

print(f"Updated Radius: {radius}")
print(f"New Age: {user_age}")
print(f"New Temperature: {temperature}°F")
print()

# Multiple variables in one print statement
print("=== MULTIPLE VALUES IN PRINT ===")
print("User Info:", user_name, user_age, is_active)
print(f"Circle - Radius: {radius}, Area: {PI * radius ** 2:.2f}")
print()

# Different ways to use print function
print("=== PRINT FUNCTION VARIATIONS ===")
print("Hello," + " " + "World!")  # String concatenation
print("The value is:", 42)        # Multiple arguments
print("Line 1", end=" ")          # Changing end character
print("Line 2 on same line")
print("Escape\ncharacters")       # Using escape sequences
print()

# Formatting output
print("=== FORMATTED OUTPUT ===")
print(f"Circle Area: {PI * radius ** 2:.3f}")
print("User: {} (Age: {})".format(user_name, user_age))
print("Gravity: %.2f m/s²" % GRAVITY)
